    , notes := "The Awodey-Butz branch now supports the first categorical operations actually needed for semantics: terminal objects, fiber products over a base, pullback/reindexing along continuous maps, and functorial behavior of sections under those constructions. On top of that, the live code stages the proposition/base-sort fragment of typed semantics, with simple-type constants interpreted as global sections, simple contexts interpreted by iterated fiber products, context morphisms as slice maps over the base, and terms reindexed honestly by composition along those morphisms. The newest layers turn proposition-valued context terms into a first live predicate fibration fragment in the spirit of Jacobs: they add predicates as `prop`-typed terms, generic variables and generic propositions in extended context, weakening, the key decomposition law saying a substitution into an extended context is exactly its head term plus its tail substitution, explicit equivalences packaging substitutions into extended contexts and proposition contexts as split-fibration style data, a clean de Bruijn variable semantics with checked substitution-at-head lemmas, a tiny syntactic term/substitution layer with explicit substitution composition whose semantic interpretation satisfies both the expected substitution law and semantic composition law, a matching syntactic split-fibration package where substitutions into an extended context are packaged by `head` and `tail`, substitutions into the empty context are shown unique, evaluation lands exactly in the already-live semantic `CtxHom.splitEquiv`, a one-variable proposition-context bridge identifying syntactic proposition terms with substitutions into the proposition context, a first real propositional fragment with `⊤`, `⊥`, `∧`, `∨`, and `→`, interpreted by staged predicate operations and satisfying a fully checked syntactic-substitution/semantic-reindexing theorem, a direct proof-spine bridge embedding the live simple fragment back into the native HOL syntax via `toCtx`, `toVar`, `toTerm`, `toSubst`, and `toFormula`, a native semilocal-model bridge transporting propositional derivations into direct simple-fragment semantic truth, a first quantified simple layer with `∀` and `∃`, lifted substitutions, a direct quantified semilocal evaluator equal to native `formulaTruth`, quantified substitution compatibility, and sound transport of native quantified derivations into both semilocal and global simple-fragment truth, an actual topological quantified layer on `Pred` itself with lifted context morphisms under binders, semantic weakening and lifted-substitution lemmas on the Awodey-Butz side, an abstract quantified interpretation with reindexing laws for `∀` and `∃`, a direct quantified evaluator into section semantics with a checked substitution/reindex theorem, a stronger theorem-level global-model bridge for that topological fragment via one-point etale semantics induced from any global model, exact comparison between topological quantified evaluation and native model evaluation, an environment-extensionality theorem for semilocal evaluation, direct transport of native derivability into the actual Awodey-Butz `Pred` semantics for closed formulas, an explicit topological antecedent/validity layer for translated simple sequents via `truthAntecedent`, `TruthValidSequent`, and `truthValidSequent_of_translated`, the first direct countermodel-to-non-derivability bridge on that topological side via `not_derivable_of_truth_counterexample` and `not_derivable_of_closed_truth_ne_top`, and now beta-specialized higher-order packaging on top of the one-point bridge via `truthEval_beta`, `not_derivable_of_beta_truth_counterexample`, and `not_derivable_of_exists_beta_truth_counterexample`. The branch also includes five archive-free higher-order lifts: a reusable full-type context/term-in-context API for arbitrary semantic type families via `EtaleSpace.BasicTopologicalInterpretation`, a matching native de Bruijn variable semantics on that API with checked substitution-at-head lemmas, a first higher-order one-point bridge for the full native HOL syntax over all types via direct topological evaluation by native semantics with direct variable-to-environment agreement in the point model, a first applicative higher-order fragment with native `var`/`const`/`app`/`lam` syntax, a minimal topological applicative interface, and a checked one-point evaluation theorem matching native HOL semantics, and an archive-free substitution/renaming layer for that applicative fragment via `ApplicativeSubst`, `ApplicativeTerm.rename`, `ApplicativeTerm.subst`, translation theorems back to native HOL substitution, and a point-model evaluation-under-substitution theorem. General exponentials and the full sheaf-level higher-order internal language remain future work." }
