    , notes := "The Awodey-Butz branch now extends to the full HOL type system including arrow types. Exponential étale spaces (internal hom) provide the categorical interpretation of function types: E^F is the étale space of germs of local morphisms F → E. The full `TopologicalInterpretation` interprets all types including arrows via exponentials, contexts as fiber products, variables via projection, constants via pullback of global sections, lambda abstraction via curry, and application via eval. The semantic evaluator now exposes the beta-redex law `TopologicalInterpretation.eval_app_lam`, and the completeness-facing semantics/bridge layers now package that seam as `awodey_butz_completeness_of_exists_beta_truth_counterexample`, `awodey_butz_completeness_bridge_of_exists_beta_truth_counterexample`, `CompletenessFrontier.awodey_butz_completeness_of_exists_beta_truth_counterexample`, `CertifiedCountermodelCandidate.awodey_butz_completeness_of_exists_beta_truth_counterexample`, `CertifiedCountermodelCandidate.awodey_butz_completeness_of_exists_closed_beta_truth_counterexample`, and `CertifiedCountermodelCandidate.awodey_butz_completeness_of_exists_closed_beta_succedent_counterexample`, so downstream topological consumers can use the proved beta path at the semantics, bridge, frontier, candidate, closed-candidate, and actual closed-succedent-consumer levels instead of reimplementing lambda/application reasoning by hand. The main remaining gaps are the connective and quantifier interpretation details outside the Heyting layer, plus the stronger completeness bridge itself." }
